nodes.name: Chandler Petersen
nodes.about: Chandler Petersen is a second-year PhD student in the Allen School, advised by Georg Seelig. His research area is DNA computing and molecular programming. Petersen works to scale up the synthesis, computation and readout of DNA logic circuits using next-generation sequencing and is developing tools to better visualize and teach DNA strand displacement circuits. He also serves as a teaching assistant and engages in outreach to help students understand molecular computing.

nodes.name: Shane Colburn
nodes.about: Shane Colburn completed his Ph.D. at UW and designs hybrid optical-digital imaging systems that exploit dielectric metasurfaces. His research introduces metasurface optics to mitigate optical aberrations and develops reconfigurable meta-surfaces using electromechanical tuning and phase-change materials. He now directs system design at Tunoptix, using meta-optics to create compact imaging systems.

nodes.name: Luke Snyder
nodes.about: Luke Snyder is a computer science PhD student at the University of Washington, advised by Jeffrey Heer. He previously earned a master's degree at Purdue University, where he worked on predictive visual analytics of social media data. His current research interests span human-computer interaction, scholarly communication and data visualization Snyder focuses on designing intelligent interfaces and visualization tools that help people communicate and analyze information effectively. He explores interaction design techniques to make data exploration intuitive and leverages AI to support user workflows. By combining HCI and visualization, he aims to advance tools that aid researchers and the public in understanding complex information.

nodes.name: Paresh Chaudhary
nodes.about: Paresh Chaudhary's research examines how to improve cooperation between artificial agents and humans. In his work on Generative Online Adversarial Training (GOAT), he combines a pretrained generative model with adversarial training to sample realistic but challenging partner policies for a cooperative agent. GOAT dynamically searches the generative model's latent space for coordination strategies where the learning agent underperforms, thereby exposing the cooperator to diverse interaction scenarios and improving generalization to novel human behaviors. This framework yields state-of-the-art performance on Overcooked benchmarks and demonstrates how adversarial training can be adapted to cooperative human-AI settings.

nodes.name: Walterio Mayol

nodes.about: Walterio Mayol is a principal research scientist at Amazon and an industry advisor to the UW Reality Lab. He has a long history of research in wearable computing and AR, including early head-mounted displays and portable sensor systems. At Amazon he leads projects on context-aware computer vision and immersive interfaces. His expertise helps guide Reality Lab research toward practical AR applications and user-centered design.

nodes.about: Matthew D. Golub directs the Systems Neuroscience & AI Lab, which sits at the intersection of neuroscience, neuroengineering, machine learning and data science. His group designs computational models and algorithms to decode how single-trial neural population activity relates to movements, decisions and learning. Their research uses probabilistic latent variable models and deep neural networks to analyze large-scale neural recordings and studies how neural populations change during learning, how decisions are formed and executed, and how brain-computer interfaces can provide insight into neural computation. Golub's postdoctoral work at Stanford employed deep-learning techniques to understand population-level neural computations underlying perceptual decision making. He collaborates widely with experimental groups to develop new analysis methods that bridge systems neuroscience and AI.

nodes.name: Samantha Borje
nodes.about: Samantha Borje is a graduate student in MISL working with Georg Seelig and Jeff Nivala. She is scaling up DNA strand displacement circuit architectures to implement more complex molecular computations. Borje is also developing CRISPR-based systems that enable neural network-like computation inside living cells, with potential applications in disease diagnostics, environmental monitoring and synthetic biology.

nodes.name: Josh Horowitz
nodes.about: Josh Horowitz is a PhD student in the Interactive Data Lab and a member of the research collective Ink & Switch. He designs new forms of dynamic media and end-user programming systems that empower people to build and share interactive artefacts. His projects explore computational substrates, convivial and equitable computing, visualization, learning communities and tangible or spatial computing Horowitz creates creative tools that lower the barrier to programming through techniques such as programming by demonstration and malleable software, and he engages with communities of learners and makers to understand their needs. By combining human-computer interaction, graphics and visualization, he aims to make computing more expressive and accessible.

nodes.name: Stella Li
nodes.about: Stella Li is a second-year PhD student in the Allen School's Tsvetshop, advised by Yulia Tsvetkov. Her research combines natural language processing and cognitive modeling to improve healthcare and wellness. She studies how humans reason, communicate uncertainty and make decisions in complex domains such as medical care, and she uses these insights to build socially and cognitively aligned NLP systems. Her long-term goal is to develop AI systems that can support clinicians and patients by providing reliable, equitable and empathetic decision support. Her current projects focus on AI for health, safety and reliability, proactive learning and social reasoning, aiming to make NLP models more trustworthy and aligned with human values.

nodes.name: Huichen (Will) Wang
nodes.about: Huichen (Will) Wang is a PhD student co-advised by Jeffrey Heer and Leilani Battle in the Interactive Data Lab. His research bridges generative AI and HCI to create human-centric tools for information visualization and data science. He examines the capabilities of foundation models for visualization and develops benchmarks and datasets such as FullFront (a benchmark for front-end engineering skills), Grid Labeling (a crowdsourced saliency labeling dataset for charts), and EMMA (a multimodal benchmark evaluating model perception of charts and language) Wang also designs interfaces like Jupybara for LLM-based data analysis and DracoGPT for extracting model preferences in visualization design, and he studies how people trust AI explanations in visual analytics Through these efforts he seeks to evaluate and improve the generative capabilities of AI for visualization while ensuring that human cognitive and perceptual factors remain central

His research focuses on leveraging big data and machine learning to understand urban dynamics and inform city planning. He develops visualization tools that help stakeholders explore urban datasets, designs interactive systems for citizen participation in planning, and applies deep learning to model mobility and land-use patterns. By bridging HCI and urban science, he aims to make urban planning more data-driven and participatory.

nodes.name: Yile (Michael) Gu
nodes.about: Michael (Yile) is a PhD student in the SAMPL group advised by Luis Ceze. He works on scaling machine learning systems across clusters and optimizing communication and computation patterns. His research includes developing compiler passes that partition and schedule workloads for distributed training, integrating with TVM for kernel optimization, and designing runtime systems that manage synchronization and data movement. His goal is to make training large models efficient and accessible on heterogeneous hardware.

nodes.name: Marius Memmel
nodes.about: Marius Memmel is a Ph.D. student at the University of Washington supervised by Dieter Fox and Abhishek Gupta. He has interned at NVIDIA's Seattle Robotics Lab and Bosch, and holds a master's degree from TU Darmstadt where he studied computer vision and robot learning. His research involves robot manipulation, computer vision and reinforcement learning, working on projects such as world-model training and large-scale robot manipulation datasets.

nodes.name: Linda Shapiro
nodes.about: Linda Shapiro's research spans computer vision, image and multimedia database systems and artificial intelligence. She pioneered knowledge-based 3-D object recognition and experimental machine vision systems. Her current projects include robot vision, analysis of cancer biopsies and brain images, and semantic segmentation for medical and robotics applications.

His research tackles multi-agent reinforcement learning problems such as crowd motion prediction and robot navigation, and he has developed personalized reinforcement learning from human feedback and multi-task learning frameworks that enable robots to adapt to human behaviors. Poddar previously earned combined bachelor's and master's degrees from IIT Kharagpur, where he worked on multi-agent RL; his ongoing projects explore how robots can learn efficiently from interactions and coordinate with other agents.

nodes.about: Mengyi Shan is a Ph.D. student in the GRAIL lab who works on generative AI for creative content. Her GenEscape framework decomposes escape-room puzzle generation into functional design, scene-graph reasoning, layout synthesis and image editing. By coordinating multiple agents, the system generates visually coherent and solvable puzzles, demonstrating hierarchical multi-agent generation for creative tasks. Her broader interests include generative models for creative storytelling and scene synthesis.

He developed high-quality background matting techniques (CVPR 2021 Best Student Paper Honorable Mention) and takes a user-centric approach to create AI frameworks that democratize high-quality video production.

nodes.about: Maya Cakmak is a professor who directs the Human-Centered Robotics Lab. Her research aims to make personal robot assistants a reality by enabling robots to be programmed and controlled by people with diverse needs. With a background including a Ph.D. in Robotics from Georgia Tech and a postdoc at Willow Garage, she studies human-robot interaction, end-user programming and assistive robotics. Cakmak adopts a human-centered approach: her lab develops tele-operation toolkits and customizable interfaces for people with motor impairments and engages users in the design and evaluation of robot systems. The group focuses on long-term deployment of assistive robots in homes, accessible programming interfaces and shared autonomy to enhance independence and inclusion for older adults and individuals with disabilities.

She is improving a Cas9-based molecular similarity search architecture, designing computing abstractions for molecular data processing and exploring environmentally sustainable storage options that reduce energy consumption.

nodes.name: Jiexin Ding
nodes.about: Jiexin Ding's research focuses on creating new input devices for extended-reality (XR) systems. In the FlowRing project, he designed a ring-form factor device that supports dual-mode interaction: users can perform five subtle microgestures for on-the-go input and use the ring as a 2D continuous input device on surfaces. A gating classifier switches between gesture and continuous-tracking modes, and a convolutional neural network combined with an LSTM classifies microgestures using data from a contact microphone, optical-flow sensor and six-degree-of-freedom inertial measurement unit. The device achieves 93.6 % microgesture recognition across sessions (85.2 % on unseen users) and aims to bridge high-throughput stationary input with subtle mobile interactions for XR.

nodes.about: Jingwei Ma is a researcher who designs human-robot systems for accessibility and mapping. Projects such as FlyMeThrough enable autonomous drone navigation to capture immersive 3-D flythrough videos, while DIAM uses smartphone scanning to build accessible indoor maps and automatically generates floor plans for mobility-impaired users. His work aims to make 3-D reconstruction and mapping technology accessible to everyone, combining robotics, computer vision and HCI.

nodes.name: Ainaz Eftekhar
nodes.about: Eftekhar's website notes PhD work co-advised by Farhadi and Krishna and research with AI2 PRIOR. Publications include ICLR-spotlight work on selective visual representations for embodied AI, co-design frameworks for robot morphology/policy (LOKI), and recent submissions on multimodal pointing (PointArena) and generalist indoor navigation (RING). Her research targets scalable, robust perception-and-policy pipelines that generalize across embodiments and tasks.

nodes.name: Ryan Maas
nodes.about: Ryan Maas is an assistant teaching professor in the Allen School, where he teaches computer science courses and contributes to database research. As part of his master's thesis with Magdalena Balazinska he developed methods for scaling linear algebra algorithms to run efficiently on distributed database systems. Supported by an NSF IGERT fellowship, this work explored how to integrate high-performance numerical computation with relational data management to support data-science workloads. In his current role, Maas focuses on pedagogy and on bridging the gap between database systems and machine-learning operations.

nodes.about: Dan Suciu is the Microsoft Endowed Professor of Computer Science who studies the formal underpinnings of data management and applies them to emerging data challenges. His research has pioneered work on semistructured data, probabilistic databases, parallel query evaluation and causal reasoning; he also explores information-theoretic approaches to cardinality estimation and efficient recursive queries. Suciu's broader interests include query optimization, data pricing, parallel data processing and data security, and he has co-authored two books on web data and probabilistic databases. He is a Fellow of the ACM and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and has received the SIGMOD Codd Innovation Award along with multiple best paper and test-of-time awards for his influential contributions to database theory and systems.

He has contributed to global illumination algorithms, image-based rendering, and high dynamic range imaging. His work on radiosity and the Photon Map is fundamental to realistic rendering, and he has pioneered interactive methods for capturing and editing photographs. His guidance bridges industry and academia in advancing computational photography and VR.

He coordinates partnerships, manages funding and logistics, and facilitates communication between researchers and industry partners. While he does not conduct research himself, his role is critical in enabling projects in computer vision, graphics, and immersive media.

Her research centers on molecular computing-developing strategies to encode equations and computations using molecular arrangements rather than electronic circuits. Working with biologists, chemists and engineers, she analyzes data from wet-lab experiments and tackles challenges such as measuring and comparing the energy consumption of traditional processors and molecular systems. Queen's work explores the energy costs of synthesizing DNA and examines how molecular processors could enable more sustainable computing.

nodes.name: Deniz Nazarova
nodes.about: Deniz Nazarova is a first-year PhD student in the Behavioral Data Science Group and Tsvetshop, co-advised by Tim Althoff and Yulia Tsvetkov. She is interested in applying AI and NLP to therapeutic contexts, including mental health support and therapy. Her interests also span multilingual NLP, AI bias, neuro-symbolic AI, human-computer interaction and socially responsible AI. Before her PhD she worked as an AI engineer for mental health startups, which informs her goal of developing NLP systems that are equitable and beneficial for diverse populations.

nodes.name: Aleksander Hołynski

After earning his Ph.D. at the University of Washington, he worked as a postdoctoral researcher at UC Berkeley (BAIR). His research combines computer vision, computer graphics and machine learning, with a focus on generative models for video. He helped develop state-of-the-art video generation models Veo 2 and Veo 3, and his work has received best paper awards at ICCV 2023, CVPR 2024 and CVPR 2025.

His projects range from environmental RNA detection for monitoring viral presence in urban infrastructure to smartphone-based oximetry and blood glucose testing that leverage deep learning and low-cost electronics. The goal of his research is to build accessible diagnostic technologies that democratize health monitoring.

She develops compressed representations for streaming media and neural video codecs, spanning 3-D and 4-D representations, visual perception, and systems and networking. nodes.name: Farshid Salemi Parizi
nodes.about: Farshid Salemi Parizi develops wearable sensors that enable high-fidelity input for augmented and virtual reality. He co-led the development of AuraRing, a ring and wristband system that uses electromagnetic tracking to estimate the ring's five-degree-of-freedom pose with 0.1 mm resolution while consuming only 2.3 mW of power. He also helped create GlucoScreen, a smartphone-powered blood glucose test strip that uses photodiodes to draw power from a phone's flash, eliminating the need for batteries. His work enables continuous sensing and interaction for AR/VR and health applications.

nodes.name: Yifan Wang

papers.title: SunStage: Portrait Reconstruction and Relighting using the Sun as a Light Stage

nodes.about: Yifan Wang recently completed a Ph.D. at the University of Washington and now works as a research scientist at Meta Reality Labs. He develops pipelines for inferring depth, occlusion, lighting and shadow information from video sequences by analyzing the motion of people and objects, enabling automatic compositing of new objects with correct scale, lighting and shadows. His research also spans text-guided high-resolution diffusion texture synthesis, portrait reconstruction and relighting using the sun as a light stage, and depth estimation from dynamic occlusion cues.

nodes.name: Poojita Garg
nodes.about: Poojita Garg, a new PhD student in the Ubicomp Lab, brings cross-disciplinary experience spanning HCI, AI privacy and medical imaging. She co-authored Tangible-MakeCode, a system that connects physical coding blocks to a web-based programming interface, enabling collaborative and extensible learning. Garg also developed the Subversive AI Acceptance Scale (SAIA-8), which measures how users perceive AI-generated, privacy-enhancing image modifications-work that informs the design of AI systems that protect privacy while maintaining user trust. Her earlier publications include surveys of MRI denoising, segmentation and classification for prostate cancer and studies on COVID-19 mortality risk factors, demonstrating her ability to apply machine learning to medical domains. As a doctoral student, she aims to create user-centered tools that bridge tangible input, AI-based privacy protection and healthcare imaging.

nodes.name: Nussara (Firn) Tieanklin
nodes.about: Nussara Tieanklin, known as Firn, is a PhD student in the ICTD Lab advised by Kurtis Heimerl. Her research integrates qualitative study, mixed methods and machine learning within data science for social good. She examines how chronic air pollution exposure intersects with the economic vulnerability of marginalized populations and gig workers, especially motorcycle rideshare drivers in urban Thailand, exploring income instability, limited health literacy and policy neglect. She collaborates with local nonprofits to develop public health interventions and advocate for labor policy changes based on her findings. Firn is also involved in community networks efforts to bridge the digital divide; she contributes to Seattle Community Network installations, teaches technical workshops and helps with outreach to expand connectivity and digital inclusion.

His research centers on the design of intermediate representations, scheduling strategies, and code generation for machine learning compilers. He is an active contributor to the TVM open-source project and has worked on TensorIR and other low-level IRs to represent tensor computations. His work aims to generate high-performance kernels automatically for a wide variety of CPUs, GPUs, and specialized accelerators, enabling efficient training and inference for deep learning models.

nodes.name: Christina (Ziheng) Wang
nodes.about: Christina Ziheng Wang is a Neuroscience Ph.D. student co-advised by Kayvon Daie and Matthew Golub. The Golub Lab announced that she began a joint rotation with the Daie group in January 2024 and joined as a doctoral student in June 2024. While her specific projects have not been publicly described, the joint labs study neural dynamics underlying decision making and motor control, applying machine learning models to multi-region neural recordings. Wang's work likely integrates experimental recordings from the Allen Institute for Neural Dynamics with the Golub Lab's computational methods to unravel brain-wide communication and learning.

She focuses on building assistive technologies that leverage machine learning and novel interfaces. Her projects include developing accessible design tools for people with motor impairments, creating adaptive input methods that adjust to user capabilities, and studying how interface design can reduce barriers to participation. Her work combines technical innovation with participatory design to ensure that the tools she builds meet the needs of the community.

nodes.about: Luis Ceze is a Professor in the Paul G. Allen School and CEO of OctoML. He leads multiple research groups-SAMPA (hardware/software systems), SAMPL (machine learning systems and architectures) and MISL (molecular information systems)-that explore better ways to build computing systems. Ceze's research sits at the intersection of computer architecture, programming languages, machine learning and molecular biology; his teams design hardware accelerators, optimize compilers and develop DNA-based data storage and computing platforms. His contributions span sustainable AI, hardware virtualization and novel molecular computing technologies.

nodes.name: Anran Wang
nodes.about: Anran Wang is a doctoral student in the Allen School who designs algorithms for contactless health monitoring. He developed a self-supervised machine-learning algorithm that uses smart speakers and beam-forming with multiple microphones to monitor heartbeats by locating the user and extracting heartbeat sounds. In another project he transmits random white-noise signals and subtracts them to detect tiny chest movements, enabling non-contact monitoring of infant breathing using a microphone array. His work enables low-cost, contact-free health sensing via acoustics and machine learning.

nodes.about: Professor Leah Findlater is affiliated faculty with the UW Reality Lab. Her research examines how to make emerging technologies such as AR/VR and voice assistants accessible to people with disabilities. She develops and evaluates novel interfaces-such as tactile feedback systems and adaptive speech recognition-and collaborates with the Reality Lab on projects that integrate accessibility into immersive technologies.

nodes.name: Deepali Aneja
nodes.about: Deepali Aneja is a Ph.D. student in the GRAIL lab whose research bridges computer vision, computer graphics and machine learning. She develops methods for facial expression recognition and expression transfer, and creates lip-synchronization and expression editing techniques for character animation. Her work combines machine learning with artistic insight to build performance-based 2-D animation tools and has been recognized with an Adobe Research Fellowship.

nodes.name: Weixin Deng
nodes.about: Weixin is a PhD student in the SAMPL lab working with Luis Ceze. He researches compiler frameworks for deep learning and contributes to open-source projects like TVM. His work includes building cost models and auto-tuners that automatically generate optimized kernels for a range of hardware targets and designing runtime systems that manage memory and parallelism for large-scale models. He aims to make deep learning accessible across different platforms by providing portable performance.

nodes.name: Vidya Srinivas
nodes.about: Vidya Srinivas is a PhD student in the Ubicomp Lab advised by Shwetak Patel. Her research blends human-computer interaction, systems and AI, with primary applications in speech/conversational AI and AI for health. She investigates how to design human-centered intelligent systems that offer proactive conversational coaching and personalized health advice. Srinivas previously earned a bachelor's degree in computer engineering from the University of Michigan, where she worked on embedded systems and resource-constrained machine learning, experiences that inform her work on energy-efficient LPWAN for agricultural monitoring and low-latency inference techniques. Her goal is to develop robust, accessible conversational agents and health technologies that operate effectively in resource-constrained environments.

nodes.name: John Akers
nodes.about: John Akers serves as the Director of Research and Education for the UW Reality Lab. He oversees the lab's educational programs, organizes research collaborations between students, faculty, and industry, and ensures that curriculum aligns with emerging technologies in AR/VR. His work helps translate cutting-edge research into educational opportunities and fosters interdisciplinary learning.

nodes.name: Chun‑Cheng Chang
nodes.about: A PhD student affiliated with the Ubicomp Lab, Chun-Cheng Chang investigates how voice control and touch interfaces affect driver attention. In a driving-simulator study he employed the Tactile Detection Response Task (TDRT) to quantify the cognitive workload imposed by in-vehicle voice control systems. His work identified limitations of existing protocols and aims to inform the design of automotive user interfaces that minimize distraction and improve safety. Chang's broader research interests include human factors engineering and statistical modelling of cognitive workload in interactive systems.

nodes.about: Tapan is a PhD student in the SAMPL group co-advised by Baris Kasikci and Luis Ceze. He works on compiler techniques for optimizing deep learning workloads. His contributions include developing automatic schedule search and cost-modeling algorithms for the TVM compiler stack, designing equality-saturation-based optimizers such as TASO to rewrite computational graphs, and exploring memory optimizations for inference. His research leverages machine learning to guide program transformations and aims to deliver portable performance across CPUs, GPUs, and specialized accelerators.

According to his research webpage, his interests include model collaboration, social NLP, and exploring networks and structures in language models. His work investigates how large language models can collaborate effectively, often by connecting multiple models in a network or swarm and analyzing the communication patterns that emerge. These efforts seek to improve performance on tasks such as social reasoning, dialog and multilingual understanding. His projects explore network topologies and collaborative dynamics to build more robust and social NLP systems.

nodes.about: Jennifer Mankoff is the Richard E. Ladner Professor at the UW Allen School. Her research advances accessibility through human-computer interaction and human-centered computing. She employs generative AI, data science, 3D printing and computational knitting to create tools and technologies that empower disabled people to advocate for themselves in education, health and DIY domains. Mankoff's Make4All lab focuses on giving people with disabilities voice, tools and agency by developing machine-learning-augmented fabrication tools, accessible design methods and computing platforms. Her work spans sensor design, assistive technology and socio-technical analyses of intersectional disability contexts.

She explores how generative models can simplify information, provide social and emotional support and co-design physical artifacts to improve accessibility. Glazko also studies the risks of generative AI, including built-in biases and disability bias. Her research aims to understand opportunities for generative systems to support disabled individuals and to develop guidelines for responsible deployment.

nodes.name: Brianna Lynn Wimer
nodes.about: Brianna Lynn Wimer is a PhD student at the University of Notre Dame and a visiting researcher at UW. Advised by Ronald Metoyer and Jennifer Mankoff, she focuses on human-computer interaction and accessibility. Her work seeks to make data visualization inclusive by identifying challenges faced by people with visual impairments and designing interactive representations that allow users to interact with, create and derive insights from data. As a Google PhD Fellow she crafts user-friendly visualization experiences that empower individuals with disabilities to explore complex information.

nodes.name: Lucy Li
nodes.about: Lucy Li is a postdoctoral researcher in the Tsvetshop working with Yulia Tsvetkov and Noah A. Smith. Her research integrates natural language processing, computational social science and human-centered AI. She examines the societal impact and safety of language models, develops computational sociolinguistic methods, and studies human-AI interaction to improve evaluation and usability. Her projects include exploring how language models influence cultural analytics, evaluating the effectiveness of human-AI collaborations and designing culturally competent NLP systems. Lucy will soon join the University of Wisconsin-Madison as an assistant professor and is recruiting students interested in socially responsible NLP, evaluation of human-AI interactions and inclusive language technology.

He develops models that generate or transform artistic content, integrates them into interactive tools for musicians and designers, and studies how these tools affect creative workflows. He also works on AR interfaces that blend digital and physical creation. His goal is to understand how computational assistance can enhance human creativity while preserving user agency.

nodes.name: Wei Shen
nodes.about: Wei is a PhD student advised by Baris Kasikci. His research looks at microarchitectural phenomena such as speculation, caching and thread scheduling, and how they affect the correctness and performance of concurrent programs. He develops tools to detect and mitigate microarchitectural vulnerabilities, improves debuggers and profilers for modern processors, and contributes to system software that can adapt to architectural features. His work sits at the intersection of hardware, operating systems and security.

nodes.about: Jihan Yao is a PhD student co-advised by Banghua Zhu and Yulia Tsvetkov. Her research concentrates on large foundation models, with three principal themes. First, she investigates reliability, exploring whether models can recognize when they lack knowledge and abstain, especially for high-stakes applications such as medical decision support. Second, she studies evaluation, working to identify biases in model assessments and to align evaluations with human preferences, particularly for multimodal tasks. Third, she examines alignment, developing data-centric approaches to better align large models with limited high-quality data and to enable self-improvement.

nodes.about: Aashaka Desai is a PhD student co-advised by Jennifer Mankoff and Richard Ladner. Her research examines how technology can mediate communication for d/Deaf and hard-of-hearing people. She documents the multilingual and multimodal realities of signing, speechreading, captioning and spoken language, and builds technologies that support minoritized communication practices and flexible language use. Desai's Make4All projects study the fluidity of d/Deaf/Deaf-multilingual communication and design systems that enhance access across modalities and languages.

nodes.name: Zening Qu
nodes.about: Zening Qu is a PhD student in the University of Washington's Information School and a member of the Interactive Data Lab. His specializations include data visualization and HCI, and his research seeks to design tools that help analysts explore complex datasets He has investigated how to keep multiple coordinated views consistent in visualization authoring, identifying constraints and user behaviors that should inform the design of visualization software Qu also contributes to projects exploring open-weight language models and multimodal AI, reflecting an interest in bridging visualization and machine learning. Overall, his work aims to improve the usability and expressiveness of data visualization systems.

nodes.name: Lisa Orii
nodes.about: Lisa Orii is a PhD candidate in the ICTD Lab who studies digital health technologies for low- and middle-income countries. She employs qualitative and quantitative methods and human-centered design to create health technology solutions. Her projects include developing a mobile app that educates women about contraceptive options in Kenya, designing approaches to improve the privacy of electronic HIV data in Malawi, and creating tools to record and share menopause experiences. Her work spans sexual and reproductive health, mental health, maternal and newborn care and HIV/AIDS, and she collaborates with engineers, designers and nonprofit partners to ensure that technology interventions are co-designed with local communities.

nodes.name: Claire Yang
nodes.about: Claire Yang is a Computer Science Ph.D. student who joined the Human-Centered Robotics Lab in 2024. Her research spans human-robot interaction, artificial intelligence and alignment. She aims to align robotic assistance with users' goals by learning human preferences, investigating intrinsic motivation objectives for assistive agents and developing shared autonomy systems that balance robot assistance with user control. Her first paper analyzes how robot autonomy affects user agency and was accepted to RO-MAN 2025, and she is examining the disempowerment that can occur when assistance is offered in multi-agent scenarios. Earlier, Yang's undergraduate research at the University of Minnesota focused on representing and inferring social preferences in multi-agent environments and planning for non-playable characters in games. Her overarching goal is to design assistive robots that are aligned with human values and that empower users.

nodes.name: Maureen Stone
nodes.about: Maureen Stone is an Affiliate Professor and research adjunct in the UW Interactive Data Lab, renowned for her expertise in digital color. Her research spans perception, design and interactive visualization; she seeks to understand why well-established principles of visual design are effective from cognitive and perceptual standpoints and to apply those insights to computer-generated imagery After a distinguished career at Tableau Research, Stone continues to collaborate with the Interactive Data Lab, focusing on tools that help people construct visually harmonious color palettes and improve the expressiveness of charts and dashboards By combining perceptual science with visualization design, she advances the art and science of color in data communication.

Her research sits at the intersection of computer systems, the natural sciences and environmental sustainability. Strauss investigates approaches to reduce computing's environmental impact, including hardware accelerators for machine learning, emerging memory technologies and leveraging biology, chemistry and materials to create sustainable information systems. She led the team that demonstrated the first end-to-end DNA data storage system and continues to explore broader DNA-based computation and energy-efficient AI methods such as Project Zerix and Carbonix.

nodes.about: David Salesin is a principal scientist and director at Google Research and an industry advisor to the UW Reality Lab. He is known for seminal work in non-photorealistic rendering, image-based editing, and digital photography. His research has explored how mathematical models can mimic artistic styles and has led to algorithms for pen-and-ink illustration, watercolor rendering, and interactive image composition. His leadership in industry research helps translate academic advances into creative tools.

nodes.name: Anthony Wise
nodes.about: Anthony Wise is a PhD student in the UW Interactive Data Lab advised by Leilani Battle. His research sits at the intersection of human-computer interaction and data systems. He co-developed SIMBA, an adaptive benchmark that simulates user exploration sessions over interactive dashboards by modeling analysis goals as SQL queries and measuring how quickly database management systems support those goals By generating both targeted and open-ended exploration sequences, SIMBA provides a way to evaluate and tune query engines for interactive workloads. Wise's broader goal is to develop benchmarks and tools that capture the behaviours of analysts and use these insights to optimize interactive data systems and human-AI interfaces.

She has worked on projects that use smartphones and AR headsets to capture real-world accessibility data, interactive tools that help users visualize and create physical objects, and wearable sensors that enable novel input modalities. She combines user-centered design with machine learning to prototype and evaluate new systems, aiming to improve accessibility and foster creativity.

By partnering with academic researchers, he ensures that the latest advances in neural rendering and 3D reconstruction inform commercial product development.

nodes.about: Jeffrey Heer is the Jerre D. Noe Endowed Professor of Computer Science at the University of Washington and the director of the Interactive Data Lab. His mission is to enhance people's ability to understand and communicate data by designing new interactive visualization systems and studying perceptual, cognitive and social factors that affect data analysis He and his collaborators created foundational tools such as the D3.js visualization library, the declarative Vega and Vega-Lite languages, and interactive systems like Voyager and Lyra that allow analysts to specify and explore visualizations at a high level. Heer also contributed to scalable systems like Falcon for interactive crossfiltering and to commercial tools such as Trifacta, broadening the impact of visualization research. His work has been recognized with awards including MIT Technology Review's TR35, an ACM Grace Murray Hopper Award and the IEEE Visualization Technical Achievement Award Through research, teaching and community leadership, Heer has shaped the field of data visualization and HCI.

nodes.about: Jeffrey is a PhD student in the Wildlab co-advised by Daniela Rosner and Katharina Reinecke. His research uses participatory design and storytelling to understand how technology can better serve underrepresented populations. He works with community partners to co-create digital tools that allow people to share their experiences and influence how technology is designed. His projects include designing interactive systems for civic participation and analyzing how narrative structures can affect engagement with scientific information.

nodes.name: Zoey (Qiuyu) Chen
nodes.about: Zoey (Qiuyu) Chen is a Ph.D. student in the WEIRD lab advised by Dieter Fox and Abhishek Gupta. Her research focuses on imitation learning and robot manipulation, with a particular interest in generating diverse data so that robots can learn from limited demonstrations. Her projects include URDFormer, a pipeline that predicts articulated simulation environments from real images to train robots, and GenAug, which uses image-text generative models to retarget behaviors to unseen situations and improve robot policy generalization.

He also contributes to TVM and related projects, designing kernel fusions and memory-efficient tensor layouts to accelerate generation on GPUs. His work combines compiler techniques, hardware-aware scheduling, and algorithmic innovations to improve the throughput and latency of LLM inference.

nodes.name: Courtnie Paschall
nodes.about: Courtnie Paschall is an MD-Ph.D. student at the University of Washington's Center for Neurotechnology. She develops virtual reality (VR) platforms that pair with intracranial electrode recordings to study brain-computer interfaces. Her research uses VR to conduct functional decoding, sensory restoration and neuroplasticity experiments in patients with epilepsy, demonstrating how VR provides immersive control and new directions for neuroscience research.

nodes.about: Daphne Kontogiorgos-Heintz is a PhD student in the Allen School working with Jeff Nivala in MISL. As co-lead author of a Nature paper, she helped develop a method for long-range, single-molecule protein sequencing using nanopore technology. The approach pushes proteins through a nanopore sensor multiple times to reduce noise and obtain accurate sequencing readouts. Kontogiorgos-Heintz focuses on interpreting nanopore signals to deduce amino acid sequences at the single-molecule level, enabling detection of post-translational modifications and advancing proteomics. Her work has been recognized at the UW Research Showcase, highlighting the commercial potential of single-molecule protein sequencing.

nodes.name: Kunal Jha

papers.title: Cross-environment Cooperation Enables Zero-shot Multi-agent Coordination

nodes.about: Kunal Jha's doctoral work seeks to build agents that can learn and interact like humans. Drawing on cognitive science, philosophy, economics and physics, he designs algorithms for social learning-where agents acquire skills or causal models by observing others-and theory-of-mind, allowing agents to reason about hidden mental states. His research uses deep and multi-agent reinforcement learning, energy-based and probabilistic causal models, evolutionary algorithms and game theory to foster embodied cognition. Jha's 'Cross-Environment Cooperation' framework trains agents across a distribution of environments to develop general cooperative norms and achieve zero-shot coordination with new partners, demonstrating how diverse training encourages robust cooperation.

nodes.name: Enhao Zhang
nodes.about: Enhao Zhang is a PhD candidate in the UW Database Group co-advised by Magdalena Balazinska and Ranjay Krishna. His work bridges database systems, machine learning and human-computer interaction to make video data more queryable and useful. He has built a series of video data management systems-including VOCAL, VOCAL-UDF, EQUI-VOCAL and related projects-that generate compositional video queries from natural language and visual keywords without relying on predefined task modules These systems employ large language models to synthesize user-defined functions and incorporate active learning to improve performance over time, allowing users to interactively explore scenes and relationships in video collections. Zhang's research aims to democratize access to video analysis by integrating efficient query planning from databases with the flexibility of machine learning models

nodes.name: Katelyn Xiaoying Mei
nodes.about: Katelyn is a PhD student in the Wildlab co-advised by Katharina Reinecke and Lucy Lu Wang. Her research combines HCI and NLP to understand and mitigate cultural and linguistic biases in AI systems. She conducts large-scale crowdsourced experiments to examine how people from different backgrounds perceive and interpret language on websites and in conversational agents. She also collaborates on developing evaluation metrics and model adjustments that improve fairness and inclusivity in language models. Her work informs the design of culturally adaptive interfaces and aims to make AI-driven communication more equitable.

nodes.about: Hongyu Sun is the senior director of engineering at the OPPO Seattle Research Center and serves as an industry advisor to the UW Reality Lab. His work involves developing algorithms and hardware for AR/VR devices, including optical systems, 3D reconstruction, and sensor fusion. By collaborating with academic researchers, he helps bring cutting-edge techniques in computer vision and graphics into commercial XR products.

His research focuses on leveraging AR/VR technologies to create immersive experiences that benefit people with disabilities and support educational outcomes. He designs and evaluates VR applications that provide spatial feedback, develops authoring tools that allow educators to create accessible content, and collaborates on projects that use computer vision and machine learning to enhance user interaction. He aims to make immersive media more accessible and useful for diverse populations.

nodes.about: Philip (Phil) Bernstein is a Distinguished Scientist at Microsoft Research and an affiliate faculty member at the University of Washington. Over a four-decade career, he has made seminal contributions to database systems and transaction processing. His current research explores approximate nearest neighbour search on large vector databases and investigates how disaggregated cloud resources such as SmartNICs and disaggregated memory can improve database server performance. From 2012-2019 he led the development of Orleans, a distributed actor-oriented programming framework, which he later extended to support indexing, geo-distribution and transactional consistency, effectively creating an actor-oriented database system. Earlier he co-designed the SQL Azure cloud database engine and built Hyder, a prototype scale-out transactional record manager. Bernstein also led the Model Management project for data integration and has co-authored influential books on transaction processing, reflecting his long-standing impact on database systems and data integration.

nodes.about: Esther Jang is a postdoctoral researcher at the ICTD Lab and director of the Local Connectivity Lab. She founded the Seattle Community Network to build DIY internet infrastructure for digital equity and leads projects that install community networks, teach networking skills and develop toolkits for community-owned connectivity. Her work includes the Maijuna Connectivity project, a community networks toolkit and efforts to improve rural network repair and sustainability. She combines technical development with community capacity building to ensure that connectivity initiatives empower local stakeholders and remain sustainable over time.

At the Reality Lab he leads research on neural radiance fields, virtual teleportation, and immersive video. He has received multiple test-of-time awards and ACM fellowship for his impact on the fields of computer vision and graphics.

nodes.about: Professor Katharina Reinecke directs the Wildlab at the University of Washington. Her research investigates how cultural backgrounds and cognitive differences influence the way people perceive and use technology. She pioneered LabintheWild, an online experimentation platform that has collected data from millions of participants worldwide to study cross-cultural preferences and biases. Her work spans culturally adaptive user interfaces, ethics and unintended consequences of AI, and tools that detect bias in website design and language. She collaborates with NLP researchers to examine bias in language models and develops guidelines and systems to create more inclusive digital experiences. She publishes regularly in top HCI venues and received multiple awards for her contributions to human-centered computing.

nodes.name: Thomas Furness

He invented early VR systems for aviation and defense in the 1980s and later founded VR and AR programs at UW. His ongoing work explores new display technologies, sensory substitution, and educational applications of VR. His legacy informs the lab's vision for future immersive technologies.

nodes.name: Xiyuan (Alan) Shen
nodes.about: Xiyuan (Alan) Shen is a PhD student in the Ubicomp Lab whose work spans wearable input devices and human factors. He co-developed MouseRing and WritingRing, ring-form factor devices equipped with inertial sensors that enable always-available touchpad and handwriting input. His research also quantifies how cognitive load during multitasking degrades touchscreen performance and driving safety; in a UIST 2025 study, he measured pupil diameter and electrodermal activity and found that cognitive load decreased touchscreen throughput by 58 %, increased lateral deviation by 41.9 % and lengthened movement time by 20 %, demonstrating the importance of designing interfaces that account for cognitive workload. Shen's broader goal is to create ergonomic, context-aware input devices and understand cognitive factors in human-computer interaction.

He also explores techniques for automated data augmentation and synthesis to improve generalization across modalities, with the goal of building more adaptive and trustworthy AI systems.

Liu co-authored the multi-region latent factor analysis via dynamical systems (MR-LFADS) technique, which uses deep learning to decode communication between brain regions when some areas cannot be recorded, enabling prediction of how perturbing one region affects others. Her work aims to reveal how neural circuits communicate during complex cognitive tasks and to improve analysis of large-scale electrophysiological data.

He is developing mixture-of-expert models for mobile vision transformers to achieve structured sparsity and efficient inference on devices like Raspberry Pi and Edge TPU. His main application area is wildlife monitoring for ecological conservation, and he collaborates with conservation and agriculture partners to deploy his models. She studies how virtual and augmented reality systems can accommodate diverse users, including those from different cultural backgrounds or with disabilities. She develops VR interfaces that adapt content and interaction modalities, evaluates user experience through experiments, and collaborates on projects in computational photography and 3D reconstruction. Her goal is to ensure that next-generation immersive experiences are accessible and culturally sensitive.

Takahashi co-developed PurpleDrop, a digital microfluidic device that moves droplets across an array of electrodes, and Puddle, an open-source microfluidics operating system that provides high-level primitives like mixing, splitting and heating and uses computer vision to correct errors. His work also integrates microfluidic pumps and software control to build the first fully automated DNA storage system, eliminating manual laboratory steps.

nodes.name: Henry Wong
nodes.about: Henry Wong is a Ph.D. student co-advised by Jeff Nivala and Yoshi Kohno. His research spans cyber security and molecular informatics: he develops adversarial techniques for attacking communication protocols and studies how to secure emerging molecular information systems. His background includes an M.S. and B.S. in computer science from Missouri University of Science and Technology, where his thesis demonstrated a man-in-the-middle attack on the MQTT protocol using a custom parser and a BERT-based adversarial model that generated malicious messages able to evade multiple anomaly-detection defenses. At the University of Washington, Wong applies similar adversarial and AI techniques to secure DNA-based data storage and computing platforms, and he works at Sandia National Laboratories on cyber security and AI research.

nodes.about: Mattias Tolhurst is a graduate student in MISL under Jeff Nivala. He develops synthetic biology tools to record the inner workings of cells. Tolhurst is creating a molecular recording device that uses synthetic biology to measure the age of enzymes and proteins inside cells, enabling scientists to track cellular processes over time. His work combines mathematics, biotechnology and pharmacology training to engineer molecular devices that capture temporal information.

nodes.name: Alex Ching
nodes.about: Alex Ching is a PhD student in the Ubicomp Lab whose research lies at the intersection of sensing, wearable technology and applied machine learning. He builds novel low-power systems to collect biosignal and health data and develops signal-processing and machine-learning algorithms to convert these measurements into usable health insights. Ching brings ten years of industry experience in AR/VR research and hardware prototyping and previously conducted research on finger-based pre-hypertension detection using photoplethysmography. His work aims to create unobtrusive, energy-efficient sensing platforms that empower users to monitor health outside clinical settings.

nodes.about: Zachary Englhardt is a third-year PhD student jointly advised by Vikram Iyer and Shwetak Patel. His research covers two distinct domains: first, he develops sustainable computing systems that integrate sensing, networking and actuation while adhering to stringent power, material and form-factor constraints-work that aims to enable ubiquitous, low-impact sensing and control. Second, he studies human-AI interaction by creating techniques that synthesize clinically useful analyses from longitudinal, multimodal mobile health data. By combining hardware innovation with machine learning, Englhardt seeks to create eco-friendly sensors and tools that empower health monitoring and clinical decision making.

A project listing for her NSERC-funded work on 'User-created Tangible Input Devices' notes that she investigates human-computer interaction, tangible input and spatial learning. The project explores how enabling users to build their own physical controllers can enhance spatial reasoning and learning in digital tasks. Further details about her ongoing research were not found, so a comprehensive description is unavailable.

He develops software that guides users through designing custom physical objects, integrates AR interfaces for in-situ feedback, and uses machine learning to suggest design improvements. His work helps bridge the gap between digital design and physical creation, making fabrication more accessible and engaging.

nodes.about: Jeff Nivala is a research assistant professor and co-director of the Molecular Information Systems Lab. His work focuses on improving the "molecular-to-digital interface" to make molecular information systems faster, scalable and accessible. Nivala's group integrates silicon and biomolecular systems, developing nanopore-based technologies for sequencing proteins and decoding molecular barcodes. He has pioneered single-molecule nanopore sequencing of proteins, designed nanopore-addressable molecular barcodes for data storage and communication, and explores nanopore proteomics and synthetic biology applications.

nodes.about: Magdalena Balazinska is the Director of the Paul G. Allen School and the Bill & Melinda Gates Chair. A professor of computer science, she is known for her contributions to database and distributed systems. Her current work focuses on data management for data science, cloud computing, image and video analytics, database systems for virtual and augmented reality, and the integration of machine learning with databases. Ongoing projects include VisualWorldDB for video data management, Image Analytics to support deep learning over scientific image databases, DeepQuery which leverages reinforcement learning to optimize query processing with the Cuttlefish system, and Themis for open-world data management with the EntropyDB engine. Past projects such as Myria, CQMS, Nuage and SciDB advanced cloud-based big data management and collaborative query processing. Beyond research, Balazinska has served as director of the eScience Institute and Associate Vice Provost for Data Science and has received numerous awards including the VLDB Women in Database Research Award and SIGMOD Test-of-Time Award.

nodes.name: Patrick Yin
nodes.about: Patrick Yin is a Ph.D. student at the University of Washington advised by Abhishek Gupta and supported by an NSF Graduate Research Fellowship. He studies embodied AI and builds intelligent robots, focusing on frameworks that accelerate sim-to-real transfer for robot manipulation. He co-developed Simulation-Guided Fine-Tuning (SGFT), which extracts exploration priors from simulation to speed real-world reinforcement learning, and has contributed to large datasets like DROID and Open X-Embodiment.

She developed methods for building 3D avatars from photo collections and pioneered techniques for relighting and animating faces. Her work spans neural rendering, virtual try-on, and immersive communication. She collaborates with industry partners to bring academic advances into products and has co-founded startups like Dreambit. Her research appears in top venues such as CVPR, SIGGRAPH, and ICCV.

nodes.about: Professor Jon Froehlich directs the Makeability Lab and co-directs the UW Reality Lab. His research aims to create interactive technologies that improve people's lives, with a particular emphasis on accessibility and sustainability. He and his students have developed smartphone-based tools for crowdsourcing sidewalk accessibility information, interactive textiles that sense body movement, and augmented reality systems for blind and low-vision users. He integrates machine learning with custom hardware to build sensing platforms and collaborates with urban planners to use data for better city design. Froehlich has published extensively in ACM CHI and UIST and received numerous best paper awards.

His research involves building program analyses and cost models that predict the performance of tensor programs. He works on auto-tuning frameworks that explore scheduling spaces and select optimal strategies for each target platform. By integrating these models into TVM, he helps enable automatic, hardware-aware optimization for training and inference, reducing the need for hand-tuned kernels.

nodes.about: Junran Yang is a PhD student working with Leilani Battle in the Interactive Data Lab and UW Database Group. His research focuses on developing scalable interactive data systems that seamlessly integrate database engines and visualization front-ends. Yang has contributed to projects such as VegaPlus and VegaProf, which extend declarative visualization frameworks with server-side optimization and provenance, enabling responsive and reproducible visual analysis. His paper "Optimizing Dataflow Systems for Scalable Interactive Visualization" presented techniques to push computation into the database engine to support complex visual queries at interactive speeds, while his work on "Considering Visualization Example Galleries" examined how example collections can support novice analysts Through these efforts, Yang aims to empower users to explore large datasets using high-performance visualization systems.

nodes.about: Franziska Roesner is a professor and co-director of the Security and Privacy Research Lab. Her work identifies and addresses security and privacy challenges faced by everyday users in existing and emerging technologies. She studies security and privacy implications of augmented and virtual reality, online advertising systems, and other platforms, with a focus on protecting marginalized groups.

nodes.about: Bill Howe is an associate professor in the Information School and adjunct associate professor in Computer Science & Engineering. As co-founding director of the Center for Responsible AI Systems and Experiences and director of the Urbanalytics group, he studies the epistemological foundations of AI, applying empirical methods to develop algorithms that make AI safer and more trustworthy for applications in the public sector and the physical, life and social sciences. His earlier research created systems and algorithms to democratize data science, focusing on equity, privacy and compliance, and drawing from AI, data management and visualization. Howe's group collaborates with governments and interdisciplinary researchers to build responsible AI infrastructure and to apply data science for urban and social good.

nodes.name: Shahram Izadi
nodes.standing: Industry Advisor - Senior Director of Engineering, Google
nodes.about: Shahram Izadi is a senior director of engineering at Google and an industry advisor to the UW Reality Lab. He previously co-founded PerceptiveIO and has developed systems such as Kinect Fusion for real-time 3D reconstruction. At Google he oversees AR/VR initiatives and works on spatial mapping, hand tracking, and collaborative experiences. As an advisor he provides insight into industry needs and helps shape research directions in spatial computing.

nodes.name: Shu Liang
nodes.about: Shu Liang is a research scientist at Facebook Reality Labs whose interests lie in computer vision, particularly 3-D face analysis and reconstruction. He earned his Ph.D. at the University of Washington under Linda Shapiro and Ira Kemelmacher-Shlizerman and was part of the UW Reality Lab. His publications include video-to-3-D hair modeling and head reconstruction from Internet photos, and he has interned at Oculus and Zillow.

nodes.name: Kingsley Wong
nodes.about: Kingsley Wong is a Ph.D. student in the Molecular Information Systems Lab studying how DNA can be used both as a data-storage medium and as a substrate for computation. According to the Molecular Engineering & Sciences Institute, he designs specialized molecular structures and develops strategies for DNA synthesis and sequencing to enable reliable DNA data storage and molecular computing. His prior work includes developing silicon-based DNA synthesis methods for data storage and building micro- and nanofabricated devices to measure the electrical conductivity of engineered proteins. Wong holds a B.A. in nanotechnology engineering and an M.S. in chemical engineering.

nodes.name: Alvin Cheung
nodes.about: Alvin Cheung is an associate professor at UC Berkeley and an affiliate of the UW Database Group and Reality Lab. His research combines data management, programming languages and software systems to enable end users to extract insights from large datasets and build efficient data processing pipelines. One thrust, called Verified Lifting, uses formal methods and machine learning to infer program properties and automatically optimize code for diverse platforms; this framework has been applied to database applications (QBS), stencil computations (STNG), programmable switches (Domino), parallel frameworks (Casper), GPUs (Dexter and Rake), conflict-free replicated data types (Katara) and tensor computations (Tenspiler). Cheung also designs new languages and techniques-such as Cosette, QED, Hyperloop, Spatialyze and OSD-to optimize data management and machine-learning systems. His group develops interfaces and code generators like Falx, AST-T5 and SAFIM that leverage program synthesis and machine learning to improve end-user data programming experiences. Through these projects, Cheung advances the automation and reliability of data-intensive software systems.

nodes.about: Siri Gadipudi is a master's student in electrical and computer engineering and a graduate researcher in the WEIRD lab. Her work focuses on deep reinforcement learning and autonomous robot learning. Previously she worked at the Indian Space Research Organization (ISRO), where she developed AI-driven radar tracking systems and data processing software, and now designs human-guided interventions for reset-free reinforcement learning and other robot learning projects.

nodes.about: Zhichen is a PhD student in the SAMPL lab co-advised by Luis Ceze and Zachary Tatlock. He blends techniques from programming languages and systems to design compilers that generate correct and efficient code for machine learning workloads. His projects involve developing proof-based intermediate representations for tensor programs, applying formal methods to verify transformations and equivalence, and integrating these into TVM. By ensuring correctness while optimizing performance, his work helps enable trustworthy deployment of ML systems.

nodes.about: Tyler Westenbroek draws on control theory, optimization and machine learning to develop scalable, robust and interpretable data-driven control techniques for real-world robots. He is a postdoctoral researcher at UT Austin and received his Ph.D. from UC Berkeley. His research addresses nonlinear policy optimization, reinforcement learning with simple dynamics models and Lyapunov-based control for robotic systems.

nodes.name: Rory Majule
nodes.about: Rory Majule is a graduate student in MISL advised by Jeff Nivala. His research develops digital microfluidic tools to automate bacterial and cell-free synthetic biology experiments. Majule aims to build a high-throughput, open-source platform that automates and tunes synthetic biology protocols, enabling rapid experimentation and scalable molecular information processing.

nodes.about: Yanming Wan is a second-year PhD student advised by Natasha Jaques. He is interested in building AI agents that understand human intentions and preferences so they can interact effectively with people. Wan's research combines social reinforcement learning, human preference inference and large language models; he has worked on personalized dialogue systems, methods to infer human intentions from language and reinforcement learning from human feedback. By leveraging models that reason about other agents' goals, he seeks to enable richer human-AI collaboration and decision-making.

nodes.name: Carrie Yuan (Jiayi Yuan)
nodes.about: Carrie Yuan (Jiayi Yuan) is an incoming PhD student who previously worked as a Software Development Engineer II at Amazon and holds a B.S. in neuroscience and computer science. Her research spans reinforcement learning, multi-agent learning and robotics, with the goal of applying AI to address climate and sustainability challenges. In the InvestESG project she helped develop a multi-agent reinforcement-learning benchmark that models corporate climate investment decisions and ESG disclosure mandates as an intertemporal social dilemma, showing how agents balance short-term profits against long-term climate benefits. She also contributed to the CASHER pipeline, which scales robot-learning data collection by combining real-to-sim-to-real transfer, digital twins and reinforcement learning bootstrapped with human demonstrations. Her work demonstrates how RL and robotics can be harnessed for climate action and scalable learning systems.

nodes.name: Medina Lamkin

papers.title: How Do Observable Users Decompose D3 Code? A Qualitative Study

nodes.about: Medina Lamkin is a PhD student in the UW Interactive Data Lab. Though limited biographical information is available, she co-authored a qualitative study that analyzed 715 Observable notebooks using D3.js to understand how users decompose code into program-, chart- and component-level blocks Interviews with visualization developers revealed that these decomposition levels align with how users reason about their programs and differ from formal grammars, suggesting that future visualization toolkits should accommodate the way practitioners naturally structure code. This work also identified challenges users face when maintaining multiple coordinated views, highlighting the need for software support to preserve consistency across charts Lamkin's research uses empirical studies to inform the design of programming environments for data visualization.

nodes.about: Aaleyah Lewis is a fifth-year PhD student co-advised by James Fogarty and Jennifer Mankoff. Her research lies at the intersection of accessibility and human-computer interaction, focusing on how AI-based technologies can equitably support people with disabilities who also experience other forms of marginalization. She studies the opportunities and tensions in AI systems for communication access among multilingual people with disabilities and seeks to create inclusive AI that honors intersectionality. Her work considers how race, language and disability shape access and explores generative AI and digital code-switching to design equitable communication tools.

nodes.about: Yancheng Liang is a PhD student co-advised by Natasha Jaques and Simon Shaolei Du. His research explores how intelligence arises from collective social behaviours like cooperation, adaptation, imitation, teaching and confrontation. Liang uses reinforcement learning, game theory, theoretical analysis and agent modelling to study multi-agent systems; his goal is to understand and engineer emergent phenomena such as cooperation and social norms. By leveraging analytical models from social sciences and tools from theoretical RL, he aims to develop agents that can learn to work together and adapt in complex environments.

nodes.name: Junha Roh
nodes.about: Junha Roh is a software engineer at Third Wave Automation who completed a Ph.D. at the UW Allen School advised by Ali Farhadi and Dieter Fox. His research focused on robotics and vision, particularly vision-language navigation and autonomous driving. He has worked on robotic perception and navigation systems that integrate language and vision.

nodes.name: Teerapat Jenrungrot
nodes.about: Teerapat Jenrungrot works on machine learning for audio, with a focus on simultaneous speaker localization and separation. He co-developed the Cone of Silence algorithm, which uses a deep network to isolate sources within an angular region and performs a binary search over angles to localize and separate multiple speakers in a multi-microphone recording, achieving state-of-the-art performance under high background noise.

nodes.name: Spencer Sevilla
nodes.about: Spencer Sevilla is a postdoctoral researcher and technical consultant who works closely with the ICTD Lab. He focuses on affordable internet infrastructure for underserved populations. Best known for his work on open5gs and the Community LTE Project, he deploys and supports community networks, hacks open-source communication systems, and teaches networking skills through initiatives such as the Tribal Broadband Bootcamps. His work combines hardware deployment, software development and policy advocacy to make community connectivity more accessible and sustainable.

nodes.name: Jiacheng Wu

nodes.about: Jiacheng Wu is a PhD student in the UW Database Group supervised by Dan Suciu. His work spans big data systems, relational databases and deep learning platforms, with the goal of designing data-intensive systems that exploit modern hardware such as multicores and GPUs He developed HoneyComb, a parallel worst-case optimal join algorithm that leverages multithreaded architecture to accelerate graph pattern matching, and has studied parallel recursive Datalog evaluation to improve the performance of rule-based queries on GPUs Wu's research bridges database theory and system implementation, contributing scalable algorithms and open-source systems for high-throughput data processing.

nodes.name: Arka Majumdar
nodes.about: Professor Arka Majumdar is affiliated faculty with the UW Reality Lab and works in the Department of Electrical & Computer Engineering. His research develops nanophotonic devices such as metasurfaces and nanocavities that manipulate light at sub-wavelength scales. These devices enable compact displays and sensors for AR/VR, as well as new modalities for computational imaging. By integrating optics with electronics, he aims to create efficient hardware platforms for future immersive technologies.

nodes.name: Elyas Bayati
nodes.about: Elyas Bayati is a Ph.D. student in electrical and computer engineering. He proposed a flat-optic meta-surface visor called Metaware to shrink augmented-reality headsets and increase their field of view. Bayati's research explores hybrid optical-digital systems using dielectric metasurfaces, and he has designed near-eye visors that use meta-surfaces to bend light efficiently. He also co-developed a laser-based smartphone charging system that uses safety features such as heat sinks and guard lasers to wirelessly deliver power.

nodes.name: Madeleine Grunde‑McLaughlin
nodes.about: Madeleine Grunde-McLaughlin is a fourth-year PhD student co-advised by Jeffrey Heer and Daniel Weld. Her research examines how artificial intelligence can support data-driven discovery while keeping humans in the loop. She investigates how to integrate validation, user guidance and transparency into AI-backed tools so that analysts can trust and verify the results Her work on AI chaining architectures explores how multiple models can be combined to support meaningful user interactions and robust, reproducible analysis. She has studied how data analysts respond to AI assistance and how explanations can mitigate overreliance on AI systems, and she applies these insights to domains such as environmental science By blending HCI and AI, she aims to create intelligent systems that empower users rather than replace them.

nodes.about: Yike Wang is a PhD student jointly advised by Hannaneh Hajishirzi and Yulia Tsvetkov. His research aims to build trustworthy large language models, with a particular focus on collaborative "model swarms." He investigates methods for assembling multiple language models to cooperate, exchange knowledge and abstain when uncertain. Projects such as ScienceMeter, Data Swarms, Heterogeneous Swarms, Model Swarms and Teaching LLMs to Abstain exemplify his interest in orchestrating many models and training them to recognize when they lack sufficient knowledge. Through this work he seeks to improve reliability, fairness and transparency in language models.

His work advances synthetic biology and DNA computing with applications in disease diagnostics and targeted therapy.

nodes.about: Natasha Jaques is an assistant professor at the University of Washington and senior research scientist at Google DeepMind. She directs the Social Reinforcement Learning Lab, where her group studies multi-agent reinforcement learning, learning from human feedback, human-AI cooperation and social learning. Jaques' research combines social learning and reinforcement learning to produce agents that generalize and coordinate effectively; she developed early algorithms for fine-tuning large language models with reinforcement learning from human feedback, work that later inspired industry deployment. Her contributions span social influence modelling, adversarial environment generation, emergent complexity and human-AI interaction, and her work has been recognized with a NeurIPS Best Paper award and MIT dissertation honors.

He develops deployable HCI and AI systems to make sound information accessible to Deaf and hard-of-hearing individuals, drawing on his own experiences. He has designed indoor navigation systems for visually impaired users and mentors students through accessible DIY workshops, publishing his work at CHI, ASSETS and UIST.

nodes.name: Vivek Jayaram

nodes.about: Vivek Jayaram's research lies at the intersection of machine learning, audio, music and vision. He developed Constrained Diffusion Implicit Models for fast sampling in inpainting and super-resolution tasks, personalized head-related transfer function (HRTF) estimation using everyday earbuds, Clearbuds for voice isolation and the Cone of Silence system for simultaneous source localization and separation. He also has a background in music and photography and founded the sports analytics company Fulltrack AI.

nodes.name: Ameya Patil

nodes.about: Ameya Patil is a PhD student in the UW Interactive Data Lab and Database Group, advised by Leilani Battle. His research lies at the intersection of databases, data visualization and HCI, with a focus on designing and implementing interactive systems that help researchers analyze socio-environmental data. He co-developed HydroVis, an interactive dashboard that visualizes ensemble flood forecasts to support communities in understanding and responding to flood risk, and WhaleVis, which explores historical whaling datasets through interactive charts Patil also studies visualization perception and literacy to inform the design of charts and dashboards, aiming to make complex environmental datasets more accessible and actionable for scientists and the public

nodes.name: Ananditha Raghunath
nodes.about: Ananditha Raghunath is a PhD student in the ICTD Lab whose dissertation research addresses global health and agriculture through AI-enabled technologies. She developed AI models for atrial fibrillation screening in rural Nepal using ECG data, designed chatbots powered by large language models to nudge safe treatment preferences in India, and studied the gap between imagined and real impacts of diagnostic AI in Nepal. She also evaluated language models on Indic language post-operative queries, built a smartphone LiDAR system to detect blood clotting, developed the offline agricultural directory eKichabi v2 deployed in Tanzania, investigated digital public goods distribution and smartphone-supported entrepreneurship, and explored other mobile health and agriculture projects. Her work combines mixed methods, AI development and field deployment to create technologies that support marginalized people in health and agriculture.

nodes.name: Barbara Mones
nodes.about: Barbara Mones directs the Reality Studio within the UW Reality Lab, where she combines computer graphics with storytelling. She has decades of experience in animation production and education, and her work involves mentoring students who create short films and interactive experiences using modern animation and VR tools. She collaborates with computer scientists to integrate new rendering and motion capture technologies, fostering interdisciplinary projects that blend art and technology.

nodes.name: Tingwei Shen
nodes.standing: MS Student, Human Centered Design and Engineering (HCDE)
nodes.about: Tingwei is an MS student in HCDE mentored by Daniel Campos Zamora. He works on creating digital tools and interfaces that enhance communication and mobility for people with disabilities. His projects include building web and mobile applications that collect and visualize accessibility information, using participatory design to engage users in the development process, and evaluating how these tools impact daily life. He aims to translate user insights into practical technology solutions.
