nodes.about: Leilani Battle is the Robert E. Dinning Endowed Associate Professor and co-director of the University of Washington's Interactive Data Lab. Her research aims to empower analysts by designing interactive systems for data visualization and analysis that account for human perceptual, cognitive and social factors. She develops techniques that integrate databases with human-computer interaction and visualization to enable complex, exploratory data analysis. Battle's work includes characterizing user behaviour during visual analysis to inform visualization recommendation systems and building realistic workloads and benchmarks for scalable visual analytics tools. She previously led the Battle Data Lab at the University of Maryland and has collaborated with Microsoft Research on provenance recording for data stream management systems and interfaces for debugging temporal database queries. Recognized with early-career awards, she continues to advance the integration of database systems, human-computer interaction and visualization to make data analysis accessible and effective.

nodes.name: Shyam Gollakota
nodes.about: Gollakota's UW homepage details an interdisciplinary lab that combines deep learning, signal processing, and hardware to realize previously impractical intelligent systems. His group's innovations include ambient backscatter, wind-dispersed battery-free sensors, acoustic swarms, target speech/hearing systems, and AI cameras for clinical safety; lab technologies have seen real-world impact (e.g., licensing to ResMed, startup acquisition by Google) and cross into biology and medicine through collaborations and FDA-cleared products.

His work includes designing instruction sets and microarchitectures tailored to tensor computations and building compiler backends that map high-level operators onto those primitives. He collaborates closely with hardware teams to evaluate energy efficiency and performance and aims to create end-to-end systems that deliver efficient inference and training.

nodes.about: Kyle Deeds is a PhD student in the UW Database Group, advised by Dan Suciu and Magdalena Balazinska, and an incoming assistant professor at Boston University. He researches at the intersection of databases, compilers and high-performance computing. His Galley system introduces modern query optimization for sparse tensor programs by decomposing tensor operations into aggregations using an extension of the FAQ framework and applying cost-based optimization to generate efficient sparse code He also devised partition constraints, a new statistic that partitions relations into fragments to capture latent structure and accelerate worst-case optimal join algorithms; this work received recognition at ICDT and demonstrates how database theory can yield practical speedups Beyond academic systems, Deeds is building the Govscape project to provide modern search over millions of government PDFs and aims to make high-performance computing accessible to domain experts through declarative programming and automatic program optimization

nodes.name: Johanna Karras
nodes.about: Johanna Karras is a fifth-year Ph.D. student in the GRAIL lab, advised by Ira Kemelmacher-Shlizerman, Steve Seitz and Brian Curless. Her research focuses on generative AI techniques for video and image synthesis. Projects such as HoloGarment and Fashion-VDM use synthetic 3-D assets and neural rendering to synthesize 360 degrees novel views of garments, and other works like Perturb-and-Revise and DreamPose explore generative models for fashion and 3-D editing.

nodes.about: Yihong Zhang is a fourth-year PhD student co-advised by Zachary Tatlock and Dan Suciu. His research investigates equality saturation (EqSat), a program optimization technique that represents many equivalent program rewrites simultaneously. He studies theoretical properties such as termination, develops egglog to integrate EqSat with the Datalog query language, and improves pattern-matching algorithms to make equality saturation faster and more expressive Zhang applies these techniques to domains like computational fabrication and database query optimization, demonstrating how programming-language theory can benefit data management. By unifying declarative logic programming with equality saturation, his work aims to provide a general framework for reasoning about and optimizing complex computations.

nodes.name: Dalton Hildreth
nodes.about: Dalton Hildreth applies machine learning to computer-aided design. He co-authored AutoMate, a system that uses a Structured Boundary Representation Graph Convolutional Network (SB-GCN) to learn representations of CAD parts and automatically predict how they should be mated during assembly. AutoMate releases a dataset of CAD assemblies and provides an automatic suggestion system to reduce the time required for manual assembly specification.

nodes.about: Professor Brian Curless co-directs the UW Reality Lab and is known for pioneering work in 3D reconstruction and light field rendering. He has developed algorithms for multi-view stereo reconstruction, volumetric scanning, and surface fitting that form the basis of modern 3D scanning technologies. At the Reality Lab he leads research on neural rendering, light field displays, and immersive telepresence. His contributions have been widely cited in computer graphics and vision and are used in applications ranging from motion picture visual effects to AR/VR.

nodes.about: Sudheesh Singanamalla completed his PhD at the University of Washington, where he was advised by Kurtis Heimerl and Richard Anderson. His research addressed practical ways to distribute trust in telecom infrastructure and build high-performance, transparent internet measurement systems. He studied the implications of these systems for privacy and security, and his work has been supported by the Gaetano Borriello Fellowship. After his PhD he joined Apple to work on identity and transparency infrastructure, and he previously held positions at Microsoft Research India, Cloudflare Research and Netflix, where he worked on network measurement, privacy and security.

nodes.name: Alan Wu
nodes.about: Alan Wu is a master's student at the University of Washington who collaborates with the WEIRD lab. He co-authored URDFormer, a pipeline that converts real-world images into articulated simulation scenes using generative models. URDFormer produces digital 'twins' from RGB images, enabling robots to train in simulation and transfer policies to the real world. His broader interests include simulation generation and data-driven robot manipulation.

He collaborates on projects that examine scaling bottlenecks and architectural innovation to improve performance and efficiency for emerging workloads.

nodes.name: Nikita Haduong
nodes.about: Nikita Haduong is a Ph.D. candidate advised by Noah Smith. Her research explores how artificial intelligence can support education and human creativity, including AI-assisted decision making under pressure, collaborative problem-solving environments and efficient transformer decoding. She also studies human evaluation of generated text and builds AI-assisted tools for creative expression.

nodes.name: Gary Faigin
nodes.about: Gary Faigin is an artist and author whose book 'The Artist's Complete Guide to Facial Expression' is widely used in animation and illustration. He co-founded the Gage Academy of Art and serves as a consultant for the UW Animation Production capstone. He lectures widely on facial expression and art, bringing artistic expertise to the study of human expression.

nodes.name: Konstantinos Rematas
nodes.about: Konstantinos Rematas develops deep learning methods to reconstruct 3-D scenes and create novel views from monocular videos. In the 'Soccer on Your Tabletop' project he transforms monocular soccer videos into 3-D reconstructions by estimating depth maps of each player using a convolutional neural network trained on data extracted from soccer video games and renders interactive 3-D scenes for augmented reality viewing. His research combines computer vision, graphics and machine learning to bring immersive experiences from ordinary video.

nodes.name: Emily Reif
nodes.about: Emily Reif is a PhD student at the University of Washington advised by Noah Smith and Jeffrey Heer and a senior software engineer on Google's People + AI Research team. Her research combines visualization and machine learning to make the behavior of language models transparent. She analyzes pretraining and finetuning datasets to identify how data sources shape model outputs and builds interactive tools-such as the LLM Comparator, interactive histograms and the embedding projector-to allow researchers, pathologists, writers and artists to explore model capabilities Reif's projects also include KnowYourData, which helps practitioners examine dataset composition, and the Wordcraft Writers workshop, which studies how writers collaborate with generative language models. By leveraging visualization to elucidate machine learning, she seeks to enable more responsible AI development and empower diverse users.

nodes.about: Richard Anderson is a professor of computer science at the University of Washington and director of the ICTD Lab. His research focuses on computing for the developing world. He has led and co-created several initiatives that use technology to improve education and health in low-resource settings, including the Digital Study Hall and Community Led Video Education systems for educational content, Projecting Health for video-based health training, and Open Data Kit for mobile data collection. His work also addresses digital financial services and digital health solutions in partnership with international NGOs. Beyond these projects, he has a background in algorithms, educational technology and global health, guiding the lab's mission to create socio-technical solutions that improve lives in underserved communities.

He leads projects on multimodal datasets and benchmarks (e.g., compositionality, tool use), evaluation methods for VLMs, and techniques to improve efficiency/effectiveness of data and model scaling; recent works span retrieved-real vs. synthetic training images, pruning/attention calibration for LLMs, and vision-language reasoning in video and robotics contexts.

nodes.name: Alex Ratner
nodes.about: Alex Ratner is an affiliate faculty member whose research focuses on enabling users to interact with machine-learning pipelines by programmatically building and managing training datasets. He is a co-founder of Snorkel, which pioneered the concept of weak supervision, allowing users to label, augment and structure training datasets by writing labeling functions that encode heuristics, knowledge bases or other models. By replacing manual hand-labeling with programmatic labeling and aggregation, weak supervision drastically reduces the time required to build high-quality training sets and opens new systems, algorithmic and theoretical challenges. Ratner's work has been applied to tasks ranging from chemical reaction extraction to medical imaging and natural language processing, demonstrating how programmatic labeling can accelerate the development of AI applications.

At the UW Facial Expressions Research Group he combines artistic insight with machine learning to study facial expression and create platforms for virtual worlds.

nodes.name: Lillian (Yanru) Li
nodes.about: Lillian Li is a Ph.D. student in the Systems Neuroscience & AI Lab. While specific project details are not publicly available, her research aligns with the lab's focus on developing probabilistic latent variable models and deep-learning techniques to analyze high-dimensional neural recordings. The group investigates how neural populations implement decision-making and motor-control computations and how these processes change with learning. As part of the Golub Lab, Li contributes to advancing machine learning tools for neuroscience and to collaborative studies of cognition and neuroprosthetics.

He builds deep reinforcement learning algorithms that learn in the real world and share autonomy with humans.

nodes.about: Moe Kayali is a Ph.D. student in the UW Database Group advised by Dan Suciu. His research focuses on bridging the semantic gap between complex data and practical systems by designing algorithms that operate directly on semi-structured and graph data. Kayali is interested in data management systems, AI-assisted database technologies, graph data and cybersecurity. He has co-authored several systems, including Color for graph coloring-based cardinality estimation, Mind the Data Gap for connecting large language models to enterprise data integration, and CHORUS, a foundation model for unified data discovery and exploration. Through these and other contributions, he advances scalable and secure data management techniques that leverage machine learning and graph analytics.

nodes.about: Jeong Joon Park is an assistant professor at the University of Michigan whose research integrates computer vision, computer graphics and AI. He focuses on 3-D and 4-D reconstruction and generative modeling and develops algorithms for robotics, medical imaging and scientific problems. His recent work explores generative models for physics-informed PDEs and 4-D neural fields.

nodes.advisor: Luke Zettlemoyer, Natasha Jaques, Natasha Jaques
nodes.about: Mickel Liu's work sits at the intersection of reinforcement learning, language models and multi-agent systems. He studies reinforced fine-tuning of large language models, designing self-play RL frameworks to make language models safer and more aligned; he created datasets such as BeaverTails for safety alignment and developed the Safe RLHF algorithm to incorporate human feedback in a principled way. Liu also explores multi-agent reinforcement learning for perception and control, introducing the Active3DPose scheme, which uses Shapley-value-inspired rewards and multi-agent RL to enable proactive multi-camera collaboration for 3D human pose estimation. He co-developed the MATE (Multi-Agent Tracking Environment) benchmark for target coverage control and contributed to open-sourcing the Baichuan2 large language model.

nodes.about: Lucille Njoo is a PhD student in the Tsvetshop at the University of Washington. She specializes in natural language processing, with a focus on fairness and bias in language models. She co-authored work on gendered mental health stigma in masked language models, which showed that pre-trained language models reflect societal biases by associating mental health conditions more often with women. Her research interests include developing methods to detect and mitigate such biases in NLP systems. Because limited official information is available about her research, this summary draws primarily from the gendered stigma project and her specialization in NLP.

nodes.about: Kurtis Heimerl is an associate professor at the University of Washington and a co-founder of the ICTD Lab. His research centers on technology for poverty alleviation, with a particular emphasis on providing internet access through community cellular networks. He develops low-cost, community-owned LTE networks that empower rural and underserved communities to build and manage their own connectivity, and he studies repair ecosystems and maintenance practices to ensure sustainability. He co-founded Endaga to commercialize community cellular networks and collaborates with conservation projects in Kenya to explore links between connectivity and environmental stewardship.

nodes.about: Omi's personal site notes PhD work advised by Ali Farhadi and concurrent Consulting Researcher role at Microsoft Research. His publications include similarity-preserving routers for mixture-of-experts load balancing and large-scale multi-task learning for individualized behavior modeling; broader interests include supervised/unsupervised behavioral modeling and scalable training of foundation models.

nodes.name: Safwan Diwan
nodes.about: Safwan Diwan is a graduate student in the MISL focusing on engineering novel proteins and computational tools for synthetic biology. His research interests lie in designing proteins that recognize and respond to specific molecular cues and harnessing custom protein interactions to build new biological functions or control cellular behaviour. He has developed a high-precision computational protein design pipeline combining Protein Generator, AlphaFold, RF Diffusion, ProteinMPNN and Chai-1 to improve structural fidelity and functional selectivity, constructed a novel E. coli-based assay for characterizing protein-protein interactions, and built a deep learning model that integrates chemical descriptors and drug embeddings to predict drug synergy with more than 40% improvement in mean squared error. Through these projects, Diwan integrates machine learning with molecular modeling and experimental assays to advance synthetic biology.

nodes.name: Nigini A. Oliveira
nodes.about: Nigini is a research scientist in the Wildlab. His work centers on designing and evaluating systems that detect and reduce social and cultural biases in technology. He develops interactive tools that help researchers and practitioners analyze website layouts, language use, and algorithmic outputs for fairness. He also leads field studies and online experiments to understand how technology can inadvertently disadvantage certain groups and proposes design principles to improve inclusivity. Through publications and community engagement, he advances ethical considerations in HCI and AI.

nodes.name: Alvin Cao
nodes.about: As a PhD student in the Ubicomp Lab, Alvin Cao explores how everyday devices can be used for telehealth. In the EarSteth project he co-authored, Cao and collaborators wire out the inner, ear-facing microphone of consumer active-noise-cancelling earbuds and headphones to record cardiac acoustics without specialized hardware. They train an autoencoder using digital stethoscope data to reconstruct heart sounds and evaluate the system on 23 users; the study shows that over-ear headphones yield higher fidelity heart-sound reconstruction, performance depends on device fit and user activity, and murmurs can be detected remotely. This work demonstrates the potential of consumer hearables for remote auscultation and highlights design considerations for telehealth sensing.

nodes.name: Andrzej Pronobis

His goal is to build end-to-end robotic systems that traverse the world, share autonomy with humans and extend themselves through learning. His research sits at the intersection of robotics, machine learning, deep learning, computer vision and human-robot interaction, focusing on enabling intelligent agents to perceive, explore and understand large environments to plan and execute complex tasks in collaboration with humans.

His projects include haptic controllers, scleral-coil eye tracking attachments and reconfigurable thumb-to-finger input devices. His fabrication-aware reverse engineering methods generate blueprints for carpentry by recovering semantically valid CAD assemblies from images of carpentered items.

nodes.name: Lancelot Wathieu
nodes.about: Lancelot Wathieu is a Ph.D. student in the Molecular Information Systems Lab. His research aims to bring molecular computing theory into practice by designing algorithms and compilers for DNA-based circuits. An NSF graduate fellow, he proposes to build an end-to-end automated DNA computing workflow and novel circuit designs to make molecular computing more efficient and accessible. His work explores how optimized molecular compilers and circuit architectures can translate abstract algorithms into sequences of biochemical reactions, enabling applications in therapeutics, manufacturing and computer science.

Thachuk's interests span DNA computing, molecular programming and synthetic biology, along with the design of algorithms, data structures and scientific software for molecular systems. He develops theoretical frameworks and experimental implementations of DNA-based computation and explores novel ways to harness biomolecular interactions for information processing.

nodes.name: Jeff Herron
nodes.about: Professor Jeff Herron is affiliated faculty with the UW Reality Lab. As a neurosurgeon, his research involves developing brain-computer interfaces and integrating them with AR/VR systems for neurorehabilitation and neurosurgical planning. He collaborates with engineers to build immersive platforms that can visualize neural activity and provide feedback to patients. His work sits at the intersection of neuroscience, HCI, and immersive computing.

nodes.about: Shwetak N. Patel holds the Washington Research Foundation Entrepreneurship Endowed Professorship at UW and directs the Ubicomp Lab. A leader in ubiquitous computing and sensor-enabled embedded systems, he has developed novel user-interface technologies, energy and water sensing solutions, and mobile health platforms that leverage low-power sensing, machine learning and signal processing. Patel's innovations include building-level energy monitoring (Zensi), household sensing devices (SNUPI Technologies) and numerous health-sensing systems that use commodity hardware. His work has earned the MacArthur Fellowship, Microsoft Research Faculty Fellowship, Sloan Fellowship, NSF CAREER Award and the ACM Prize in Computing. Under his leadership, the Ubicomp Lab collaborates with clinicians and industry partners to deploy sensing technologies in real-world health settings.

nodes.name: Xiaojuan Wang
nodes.about: Xiaojuan (Jeanne) Wang is a final-year Ph.D. student in the GRAIL lab, advised by Steve Seitz, Brian Curless and Ira Kemelmacher-Shlizerman. After earning a master's degree from ETH Zürich and interning at Meta, Adobe Research and Google Research, she now explores generative media and how generative AI can support visual storytelling. Her projects include 'How Animals Dance (When You're Not Looking),' which generates animal dance videos from a few keyframes, and 'Generative Inbetweening,' which adapts image-to-video diffusion models for keyframe interpolation.

nodes.about: Liangyu is a PhD student in the SAMPL group. His research explores low-level representations and compiler transformations that map high-level deep learning models onto emerging hardware. He works on designing IRs and scheduling mechanisms that can express complex tensor computations, and he helps integrate these into the TVM compiler stack. By collaborating with hardware designers, he aims to co-design accelerators and software that deliver high performance and efficiency for training and inference workloads.

nodes.name: Orevaoghene Ahia
nodes.about: Orevaoghene Ahia is a PhD student in computer science at the University of Washington, advised by Noah A. Smith and Yulia Tsvetkov. Her interests include multilingual natural language processing, model efficiency and model interpretability. She seeks to develop resource-efficient models that work well across many languages and to leverage interpretability techniques to diagnose and mitigate spurious artifacts in training data or model behaviour Before entering the PhD program, Ahia worked as a research engineer at InstaDeep. She now focuses on building models that require less computation and data while maintaining performance, and on using interpretability insights to improve cross-lingual robustness. Her work contributes to making NLP technology more inclusive and efficient.

nodes.name: Nino Migineishvili
nodes.about: Nino is a PhD student in the Wildlab co-advised by Katharina Reinecke and Rene Just. Her research sits at the intersection of HCI and software engineering. She investigates how development tools and testing frameworks can help surface ethical issues and biases in software. She designs user-facing systems that encourage developers to consider inclusivity and societal impact, and she collaborates on analyzing bias in machine learning datasets. By combining qualitative studies with tool building, she aims to make the software development lifecycle more responsible.

nodes.about: Girish Narayanswamy is a final-year PhD student in the Ubicomp Lab advised by Shwetak Patel and collaborates with Daniel McDuff and Xin Liu at Google. His research aims to expand access to healthcare by improving sensing of human physiology and behavior. He works at the intersection of artificial intelligence, signal processing and sensing and has recently developed sensor foundation models such as LSM-1, LSM-2 and SensorLM to interpret multimodal sensor data. These models unify disparate signals to provide rich representations of human activity and health, enabling new health-monitoring applications. Narayanswamy holds a B.S. in electrical and computer engineering from the University of Colorado Boulder and has industry experience through internships at Google, OctoAI, Uplinq AI, Qualcomm and Medtronic.

nodes.name: Daphne Chen

papers.title: Learning to Cooperate with Humans using Generative Agents

nodes.about: Daphne Chen is a Ph.D. student jointly affiliated with the Human-Centered Robotics Lab and the WEIRD Lab. The HCR lab notes that she started in 2023 and her research interests include robot learning and preference learning, building on master's work at Carnegie Mellon University and a bachelor's from Georgia Tech. Her recent work on learning human preferences for personalized assistance proposes a few-shot method that trains a sequential model to predict the next action in cooking tasks using synthetic data and then fine-tunes it on demonstrations from individual users, enabling assistive agents to provide guidance aligned with each person's temporal preferences with minimal data. She evaluates the approach through user studies, highlighting that assistive agents must learn user preferences quickly and data-efficiently. Chen's broader goal is to enable real-world robots to personalize their behavior to different users by combining machine learning with insights from human-computer interaction and preference modeling.
